SV, in partnership with in country partners, focuses on protection activities and access to services for refugees, IDPs, returnees, and host communities. This includes but not limited to providing legal support, child protection services, safeguarding against gender-based violence, ensuring safe spaces, and enhancing security measures to prevent exploitation and abuse. Additionally, SV supports community-led initiatives that empower local groups to identify and address their own protection needs, fostering resilience and strengthening the safety and well-being of vulnerable populations.

The ASPIRE program envisions Gender Equality and Social Inclusion (GESI) as a cornerstone of its approach, aiming to create equitable, inclusive, and sustainable initiatives. By integrating GESI principles, the program seeks to address systemic inequalities, empower marginalized groups, and foster long-term social change. This involves analyzing gender dynamics, ensuring equitable access to resources and opportunities, and adopting a "Do No Harm" approach to avoid reinforcing harmful norms.

Under the ASPIRE, SV actively fosters equitable partnerships with local, in-country organizations to ensure that all stakeholders are involved in decision-making and benefit equally from the collaboration. By emphasizing shared goals, mutual respect, sharing risks, and local ownership, SV strives to create partnerships that are not only sustainable but also inclusive, empowering local partners to drive initiatives and contribute meaningfully to their success. This approach helps bridge gaps, address disparities, and build long-term capacity within local communities, ensuring that efforts are relevant, effective, and responsive to the needs of those they aim to serve.

Construction work for 40 toilets in ongoing and reached to 40% of its completion. Rehabilitation of 20 old pit latrines (K. Kunar, Surkhrod, Goshta) is also ongoing, which includes changing pit latrines to flush toilets. Construction of 6 handwashing stations is completed, but not (yet) connected to water pipe network for supply of water to the HW stations.

First round of hygiene promotion took place in all schools, and soaps will be distributed during the third round, expected towards the end of the year (schools are currently on summer vacation until Sept). Soap will be distributed in Q4

Beneficiaries covered is 9.675 in Q3 by drilling of 6 bore wells (2 in Kuz Kunar, 3 in Surkhrud, 1 in Goshta), completed in all 6 schools. Boreholes supported by both handpumps and submersible. Handpumps in use by students and staff. Submersible not yet in use for provision of drinking water, as not yet connected with water tanks and taps. Connection work with tanks and taps planned for Q4.

In Q2 IRC successfully conducted the 1st round of hygiene promotion in the 7 targeted schools. During the session, beneficiaries learned about critical times for handwashing, personal and environmental hygiene and safe water sources and usage. In 2019, IRC provided temporary and 
emergency shelter to improve living conditions for conflict and natural disaster affected IDPs living in the open or makeshift shelters in Behsud, Kuz Kunar and Surkhrud districts of Nangahar province. The IRC provided 80 households (508 individuals - 171 girls, 160 boys, 96 women , 81 men) with temporary shelters which ensured dignity, improved quality of life, and provided an immediate solution to those families living under the open sky.
